<PART LBL="II"><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="61210">Interprocess Communication</TITLE><PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="46302" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;2, &ldquo;Interprocess Communication&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Provides an overview of the different communication mechanisms, and describes the POSIX, System V, and BSD compatibility features.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="28345" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;3, &ldquo;Sharing Memory Between Processes&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes the different ways of sharing segments of memory between different processes.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="82386" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;4, &ldquo;Mutual Exclusion&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes semaphores, locks, and other means of synchronization and exclusion between processes and threads.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="89823" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;5, &ldquo;Signalling Events&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes the different interfaces to UNIX signals, and the interval timer facilities.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD></BOLD><XREF IDREF="48324" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;6, &ldquo;Message Queues&rdquo;</XREF><BOLD></BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Describes two different facilities for creating and using message queues.</PARAGRAPH>
